{"body":"`fetchApi` now always requires a real Firebase user via `tokenManager.getCurrentUser()` / `firebase.auth().currentUser`. This bypasses `authTokenManager.getAuthHeaders()` / `getEffectiveUser()` which supports dev `?test_mode=true` auth bypass, so test mode requests will fail with "User not authenticated" even though headers could be generated. Consider using `await tokenManager.getEffectiveUser()` (or simply rely on `getAuthHeaders()` without separately requiring `currentUser`) so test-mode flows keep working.","diff_hunk":"@@ -110,47 +110,34 @@ async function fetchApi(path, options = {}, retryCount = 0) {
     }
   }

-  // Check for test mode bypass
+  // Authentication flow
   let defaultHeaders = { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' };
   const tokenManager = window.authTokenManager;
   const forceRefresh = retryCount > 0;

-  if (window.testAuthBypass && window.testAuthBypass.enabled) {
-    defaultHeaders = {
-      ...defaultHeaders,
-      ...(tokenManager?.getAuthHeaders
-        ? await tokenManager.getAuthHeaders(forceRefresh)
-        : {
-            'X-Test-Bypass-Auth': 'true',
-            'X-Test-User-ID': window.testAuthBypass.userId,
-          }),
-    };
-  } else {
-    // Normal authentication flow
-    const user = tokenManager?.getCurrentUser
-      ? tokenManager.getCurrentUser()
-      : firebase.auth().currentUser;
-    if (!user) {
-      console.error('🔴 fetchApi: User not authenticated - firebase.auth().currentUser is null');
-      console.error('🔴 fetchApi: Path was:', path);
-      throw new Error('User not authenticated');
-    }
+  const user = tokenManager?.getCurrentUser
+    ? tokenManager.getCurrentUser()
+    : firebase.auth().currentUser;
+  if (!user) {
+    console.error('🔴 fetchApi: User not authenticated - firebase.auth().currentUser is null');
+    console.error('🔴 fetchApi: Path was:', path);
+    throw new Error('User not authenticated');
+  }","id":2806764414,"line":null,"path":"mvp_site/frontend_v1/api.js","state":"open"}
{"body":"### Duplicate settings initialization on page load

**Low Severity**

<!-- DESCRIPTION START -->
A second `DOMContentLoaded` setup block was added while `window.initializeSettingsControls()` already initializes listeners and calls `loadSettings()`. This duplicates initialization paths in `settings.js`, causing repeated `/api/settings` loads and overlapping event wiring, which increases request noise and makes settings behavior harder to reason about.
<!-- DESCRIPTION END -->

